          "id": 54492,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Upper and lower endoscopy</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">An elderly female is being evaluated by her family physician for significant weight loss. Over the past 10 weeks, she has developed a velvety hyperpigmentation of the skin on the posterior neck and bilateral axilla. Her routine blood work is normal except for a hemoglobin level of 8.6 g/dL. Her HbA1c is 5.4%, and a plain chest radiograph is normal. What is the next step in the evaluation?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4831229",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32327,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Upper and lower endoscopy</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Upper and lower endoscopy </strong>is the most appropriate next step because<strong> acanthosis nigricans in a patient without obesity or diabetes </strong>suggests a possible underlying<strong> gastrointestinal malignancy</strong>, such as <strong>gastric adenocarcinoma.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A.&nbsp;A bone scan</strong> might be useful in evaluating<strong> bone metastasis </strong>if there's suspicion for a <strong>metastatic process</strong>, but it's<strong> not the first step </strong>in the evaluation of a patient with <strong>suspected gastrointestinal malignancy and acanthosis nigricans.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B.&nbsp;</strong>While a<strong> CT chest with contrast </strong>could identify <strong>thoracic pathology</strong>, it <strong>wouldn't be </strong>the initial investigation for suspected <strong>gastric malignancy</strong>, especially with<strong> normal chest X-ray findings and the presence of acanthosis nigricans</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C.&nbsp;</strong>A <strong>skin biopsy </strong>could confirm<strong> acanthosis nigricans </strong>but <strong>wouldn't </strong>address the underlying cause of the<strong> patient's systemic symptoms and weight loss.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">In an<strong> elderly patient </strong>without<strong> obesity or diabetes, </strong>the presence of <strong>acanthosis nigricans </strong>and significant <strong>weight loss </strong>is concerning for an <strong>underlying malignancy, particularly gastrointestinal in origin</strong>, thus warranting <strong>endoscopic evaluation.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Acanthosis nigricans: benign vs malignant:</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/image_YEYkQnA.png\" width=\"1156\" height=\"428\"></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease 10th edition page:329</strong></span></p>",
